translation, and the material text.Newton explores the ethics of reading through a range of texts, from the Talmud and Midrash to Conrad's Nostromo and Pascal's Le Mémorial, from works by Henry Darger and Martin Scorsese to the National September 11 Memorial and a synagogue in Havana, Cuba. In separate chapters, he conducts masterly treatments of Emmanuel Levinas, Mikhail Bakhtin, and Stanley Cavell by emphasizing their performances as readers-a trebled orientation to Talmud, novel, and theater/film. To Make the Hands Impure stages the encounter of literary experience and scriptural traditions-the difficult and the holy-through an ambitious, singular, and innovative approach marked in equal measure by erudition and imaginative daring.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aArt and morals. 0aEthics in literature. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny20th century. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny21st century. 0aReader-response criticism. 4a"the book". 4aEdward Said. 4aEmmanuel Levinas. 4aEthics of Reading. 4aHands. 4aHermeneutics. 4aMateriality. 4aMikhail Bakhtin. 4aProximity. 4aScriputre. 4aStanley Cavell. 4aText. 4aethics. 4atouch/tactility. 4atum'at yadayim. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823273324zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823273324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823273324.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK